In IncidentUsageService.cs, the current segregation logic is wrong.

CURRENT (wrong):
We are only checking ReportingSource = "automation" to classify 
an incident as "automation_tool". This is incorrect because users 
can manually change the ReportingSource value in Remedy to "automation" 
even for FrontDoor incidents.

CORRECT logic:
An incident is "automation_tool" ONLY IF BOTH conditions are true:
  Condition 1 — ReportingSource == "automation"  (from Remedy)
  Condition 2 — Submitter == account name    (from Remedy)

If either condition is false → it is "frontdoor".

---

CHANGE 1 — Environment-aware service account name

Add a private method or property that returns the correct 
service account name based on the current environment:

- Read the environment from configuration 
  (use IConfiguration or IWebHostEnvironment, whichever is 
  already used in other services in this project)
- If environment is Production → return "svc.itsm-wrkflw"
- If environment is anything else (dev, staging, nonprod) 
  → return "svc.itsm-wrkflw-dev"

Example:
private string GetServiceAccountName()
{
    return _env.IsProduction() 
        ? "prod" 
        : "dev";
}

---

CHANGE 2 — Make sure Remedy API response includes Submitter field

When we call the Remedy API to fetch incidents, make sure the 
response model (the Remedy incident DTO / mapping class) includes:
  - Submitter   (the person/account who submitted the incident)
  - ReportingSource  (already present)

If Submitter is not currently mapped in the Remedy response DTO, 
add it now. The field name in Remedy API response is [whatever 
the actual Remedy API field name is — check the existing Remedy 
API response and map it correctly].

---

CHANGE 3 — Update the cross-reference logic

Replace the current classification logic with this:

string serviceAccount = GetServiceAccountName();

bool IsAutomationToolIncident(RemedyIncidentDto incident)
{
    return 
        !string.IsNullOrEmpty(incident.Submitter) &&
        incident.Submitter.Equals(serviceAccount, 
            StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase) 
        &&
        !string.IsNullOrEmpty(incident.ReportingSource) &&
        incident.ReportingSource.Equals("automation", 
            StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);
}

Use this method everywhere we currently classify an incident 
as automation_tool or frontdoor — in the main counts, 
trend grouping, and incident row list.

Remove the old logic that was only checking ReportingSource.

---

CHANGE 4 — Update IncidentRowDto source assignment

When building the IncidentRowDto list, use the same 
IsAutomationToolIncident() method:

Source = IsAutomationToolIncident(i) ? "automation_tool" : "frontdoor"

---

DO NOT change:
- Any existing Remedy API call method signatures
- Any DB queries or schema
- Any frontend code
- Any other service or controller

Only change the classification logic inside IncidentUsageService.cs
and the Remedy response DTO if Submitter field is missing.

